
************ S — Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)***************
Meaning

A class should have only one reason to change.

One class = one responsibility.

BAD CODE : 
class Report
{
public:
    void generateReport()
    {
        cout << "Generating report\n";
    }

    void saveToFile()
    {
        cout << "Saving report to file\n";
    }
};

Problem

Report has 2 responsibilities:

Generate report
Save report

If file-saving changes → class changes.

GOOD EXAMPLE:
class Report
{
public:
    void generateReport()
    {
        cout << "Generating report\n";
    }
};

class ReportSaver
{
public:
    void saveToFile(Report& report)
    {
        cout << "Saving report to file\n";
    }
};

Interview Line

A class should do only one thing and have only one reason to change.

***********2. O — Open/Closed Principle (OCP)******
Meaning

Software should be:

Open for extension
Closed for modification

Add new behavior without changing old code.

BAD CODE:
class Payment
{
public:
    void pay(string type)
    {
        if(type == "UPI")
            cout << "UPI payment\n";
        else if(type == "Card")
            cout << "Card payment\n";
    }
};

Problem
Adding new payment type requires modifying existing code.

GOOD CODE:
class Payment
{
public:
    virtual void pay() = 0;
};

class UPIPayment : public Payment
{
public:
    void pay() override
    {
        cout << "UPI payment\n";
    }
};

class CardPayment : public Payment
{
public:
    void pay() override
    {
        cout << "Card payment\n";
    }
};

Interview Line

Use abstraction/polymorphism to extend behavior without modifying existing code.

**********************************L — Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)*****************************************
Meaning
Derived class should be replaceable with base class without breaking behavior.

👉 If Dog is a child of Animal, then wherever Animal is used, Dog should work correctly.

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Vehicle {
public:
    virtual void refuel() {
        cout << "Refueling vehicle\n";
    }
};

class PetrolCar : public Vehicle {
};

class ElectricCar : public Vehicle {
public:
    void refuel() override {
        throw runtime_error("Electric car doesn't use fuel");
    }
};

void fuelVehicle(Vehicle* v) {
    v->refuel();
}

int main() {
    PetrolCar p;
    ElectricCar e;

    fuelVehicle(&p); // OK
    fuelVehicle(&e); // Problem
}

Why issue?

Base class vehicle says:

Every vehicle can refuel().

But electriccar cannot truly refuel.
It changes expected behavior.

but if someone writes 
fuelVehicle(&e); // Problem

they expect normal refueling behavior from base contract.

But derived class breaks that expectation.

That is an LSP violatio

******INTERVIEW LINE****
Interview Explanation

Parent class promised:

All vehicles can refuel

But child class failed to support it.

So derived object cannot replace base object safely.

→ LSP violated.

Interview explanation (important):

You can say:

Base class should represent behavior common to all derived classes.
Here refuel() is not applicable to electric cars.
So electriccar should not inherit a contract requiring refuel().

***Better design:

Not every vehicle should have refuel().

Separate behaviors.
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class vehicle
{
public:
    virtual void start()
    {
        cout << "start vehicle" << endl;
    }
};

class fuelvehicle : public vehicle
{
public:
    virtual void refuel()
    {
        cout << "refuel vehicle" << endl;
    }
};

class petrolcar : public fuelvehicle
{
};

class electriccar : public vehicle
{
};

void processcar(fuelvehicle* p)
{
    p->refuel();
}

int main()
{
    petrolcar p1;
    processcar(&p1);

    electriccar e1;
    // processcar(&e1); ❌ not allowed

    return 0;
}

This is proper LSP.

Because:

Only fuel vehicles support refuel()
Electric cars are not forced to implement invalid behavior

This type of example is very interview-friendly because it is:

simple
realistic
clearly shows wrong inheritance design.

***********4. I — Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
Meaning
Clients should not be forced to depend on interfaces they don't use.

Large interfaces → split into smaller ones.

BAD CODE:
class Payment
{
public:
    virtual void pay() = 0;
    virtual void cashback() = 0;
};

Some payment methods may not support cashback.
class Payment
{
public:
    virtual void pay() = 0;
};

class Cashback
{
public:
    virtual void cashback() = 0;
};

***5. D — Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
Meaning
High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules.

Both should depend on abstraction.


Message Service
BAD CODE:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class EmailService
{
public:
    void sendMessage()
    {
        cout << "Email sent\n";
    }
};

class Notification
{
    EmailService email;

public:
    void notify()
    {
        email.sendMessage();
    }
};

int main()
{
    Notification n;
    n.notify();
}

Problem:

Notification directly depends on EmailService
Cannot easily switch to:
SMS
WhatsApp
Push notification

Violates DIP.

good code:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class MessageService
{
public:
    virtual void sendMessage() = 0;
};

class EmailService : public MessageService
{
public:
    void sendMessage() override
    {
        cout << "Email sent\n";
    }
};

class SMSService : public MessageService
{
public:
    void sendMessage() override
    {
        cout << "SMS sent\n";
    }
};

class Notification
{
    MessageService* service;

public:
    Notification(MessageService* s) : service(s)
    {
    }

    void notify()
    {
        service->sendMessage();
    }
};

int main()
{
    EmailService email;
    Notification n1(&email);
    n1.notify();

    SMSService sms;
    Notification n2(&sms);
    n2.notify();
}

Interview Explanation
Notification = high-level module
EmailService, SMSService = low-level modules
MessageService = abstraction

Now high-level class depends on interface, not concrete class.

This follows DIP.

One-line Interview Definition

Dependency Inversion Principle says high-level modules should depend on abstractions, not concrete implementations.


*********SUMMARY****
SOLID Principles (Quick Revision)

S — Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
→ One class should have only one responsibility / one reason to change.

Example:
Report class only generates report.
ReportSaver class saves report.

-----------------------------------

O — Open/Closed Principle (OCP)
→ Open for extension, closed for modification.

Add new functionality without changing existing code.

Use:
Inheritance + Polymorphism

-----------------------------------

L — Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
→ Derived class should safely replace base class.

If child breaks expected behavior → LSP violation.

Example:
Penguin should not inherit FlyingBird.

-----------------------------------

I — Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
→ Don't force classes to implement unused methods.

Prefer small interfaces over large/fat interfaces.

Example:
Robot should not implement eat().

-----------------------------------

D — Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
→ Depend on abstraction, not concrete class.

Use interfaces/abstract classes.

Example:
Computer depends on InputDevice, not Keyboard.

-----------------------------------

Easy Memory Trick

S → Single responsibility
O → Open/Closed
L → Replace safely
I → Small interfaces
D → Depend on abstraction

-----------------------------------

Most Used in Real Projects
SRP + OCP + DIP

-----------------------------------

Commonly Used C++ Features
- Virtual functions
- Abstract classes
- Polymorphism
- Composition
- Dependency Injection













